  "opinion": "As a mechanic in Naples with a curious mind, I've seen how science and hands-on work often get mixed up in people's minds. The gender gap in science isn't just about women being fewer in labs—it's about how society frames what 'science' even means. My dad had a PhD and my mom a bachelor's, so I grew up hearing stories of scientists who were women but got overlooked because they were 'not the type' for engineering or physics. When I work on cars, I see how men and women both struggle with the same tools but get different expectations: women might be told to 'be careful' while men are just 'fixed it.' The gap isn't a number on a chart; it's in the way people talk about who belongs in science. I think we should address it, but not by pushing women into fields they're not interested in. Instead, we should start by making science feel like a natural part of everyday life—like how I fix a car or my kids learn math through cooking. If we teach kids that science isn't just for 'boys' or 'girls' but for anyone who asks questions, the gap will shrink. It's not about changing people—it's about changing the way we see what science is. And that starts with listening more than lecturing.",
